 games section with a Roman gladiator simulation &#8230; <a class="more-link" href="http://webdevstudios.com/2013/06/03/camden-segal-another-addition-to-our-team/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Melissa Hoppe";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1496:"<p>Add another one to the list! WebDev is happy to welcome Camden Segal to our team!</p>\n<p><a href="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/image.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-7499" alt="image" src="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/image-300x295.jpg" width="300" height="295" /></a>Camden began his career as a developer at the age of 7, aiming to debut on AOL&#8217;s games section with a Roman gladiator simulation utilizing hypercard and advanced 3D renderings from Bryce 3D. The sting of rejection failed to deter Camden from his cyborgly pursuits &#8211; he went on to sell over $1500 in imaginary weapons on Second Life when he was in middle school. Camden moved on to serve as the Systems Administrator for Woodrow Wilson High School, where he definitely did not go out to lunch on duty. Eventually, He came to his senses and majored in Studio Arts at Bard College, and while his senior thesis project of macabre apps was well received, he has utilized his degree extensively in his postgraduate career.</p>\n<p>Camden brings experience in front-end development and WordPress theming to WebDev and is excited to share his drive to create accessible, compliant, and intuitive products.</p>\n<p>In his free time Camden enjoys playing and creating games. His first commercial game Panspermia is available for iOS and Android. He also enjoys eating pizza, fishing, and attempting to tame his cat Wrinkle.</p>\n<p>Welcome to the team, Camden!</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:83:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/06/03/camden-segal-another-addition-to-our-team/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:45:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"Lisa Sabin-Wilson is speaking at WordCamp Milwaukee 2013!";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:93:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/30/lisa-sabin-wilson-is-speaking-at-wordcamp-milwaukee-2013/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:102:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/30/lisa-sabin-wilson-is-speaking-at-wordcamp-milwaukee-2013/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 30 May 2013 19:19:15 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Team";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"WordCamp";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"http://webdevstudios.com/?p=7502";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:434:"Lisa Sabin-Wilson is at it again! This time, she will be speaking at WordCamp Milwaukee 2013. This event is being held Thursday, June 6th &#8211; Sunday, June 9th at Bucketworks. Lisa is speaking about Scoping Projects to Avoid Stress, Headaches &#8230; <a class="more-link" href="http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/30/lisa-sabin-wilson-is-speaking-at-wordcamp-milwaukee-2013/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Melissa Hoppe";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2345:"<p><a href="http://webdevstudios.com/team/lisa-sabin-wilson/">Lisa Sabin-Wilson</a> is at it again! This time, she will be speaking at <a href="http://2013.milwaukee.wordcamp.org/">WordCamp Milwaukee 2013</a>. This event is being held Thursday, June 6th &#8211; Sunday, June 9th at <a href="http://bucketworks.org/">Bucketworks</a>.</p>\n<p><a href="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/wordcamp-milwaukee-banner-2013.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-7508" alt="wordcamp-milwaukee-banner-2013" src="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/wordcamp-milwaukee-banner-2013.jpg" width="926" height="160" /></a></p>\n<p>Lisa is speaking about<a href="http://2013.milwaukee.wordcamp.org/session/scoping-projects-to-avoid-stress-headaches-and-angry-mobs-wcbizdev/"> <span style="text-decoration: underline">Scoping Projects to Avoid Stress, Headaches and Angry Mobs</span></a>. Her talk is on Saturday, June 8th at 11:00 AM.</p>\n<p><strong>Description</strong> -</p>\n<blockquote><p>Attention to detail in your code and design work is important  but before you lay down one single pixel, install your first plugin or one single line of code, you need to make sure that everyone (you, your client, your clients client, etc) are on the same page and make sure you are managing expectations on what the desired project outcome is. Learn how to dissect projects  either web site or plugin development  to determine the best approach to meet your client needs.</p>\n<p>This 45 minute covers hard lessons Ive learned in a decade of client work  I hope to pass those headaches on to you so you dont make the same mistakes. Q/A welcome, afterwards.</p></blockquote>\n<p>As always, Lisa is excited to share her knowledge with those she&#8217;s met and those she hasn&#8217;t! If you didn&#8217;t get the opportunity to pick her brain after her talk, she will be attending the after party. It is being held at 7:30 PM on Saturday, June 8th at theMilwaukee Brewing Company.</p>\n<p>Our Customer Service Rep, <a title="Melissa Hoppe" href="http://webdevstudios.com/team/melissa-hoppe/">Melissa Hoppe</a>, will also be attending WordCamp Milwaukee 2013! It&#8217;s her first WordCamp, and she&#8217;s excited to learn all that she can.</p>\n<p>If you see Lisa or Melissa, make sure you stop and say hello!</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:98:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/30/lisa-sabin-wilson-is-speaking-at-wordcamp-milwaukee-2013/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:38:"WDS welcomes Greg Rickaby to our team!";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/29/wds-welcomes-greg-rickaby-to-our-team/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:83:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/29/wds-welcomes-greg-rickaby-to-our-team/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 29 May 2013 13:14:07 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"General";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"http://webdevstudios.com/?p=7495";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:411:"WebDevStudios is very excited to announce that we are bringing on yet another great mind in the WordPress world. Welcome Greg Rickaby! Greg&#8217;s interest in web design and technology all started his Junior year in high school when he took &#8230; <a class="more-link" href="http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/29/wds-welcomes-greg-rickaby-to-our-team/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Melissa Hoppe";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2532:"<p>WebDevStudios is very excited to announce that we are bringing on yet another great mind in the WordPress world. Welcome <a title="Greg Rickaby" href="http://webdevstudios.com/team/greg-rickaby/">Greg Rickaby</a>!</p>\n<p><a href="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/greg-rickaby-a-little-goofy.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-7450" alt="greg-rickaby-a-little-goofy" src="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/greg-rickaby-a-little-goofy-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" /></a>Greg&#8217;s interest in web design and technology all started his Junior year in high school when he took a class about layout and design using Adobe PageMaker. He also dabbled in some super basic HTML on Geocities using Notepad. Throughouthigh school he worked part-time at the local radio station. Greg landed his first real job in early 2000 as Assistant Webmaster at Midwest Communications in Green Bay, WI.</p>\n<p>After a change in job and a move to Alabama, he started his own web design agency called Wildfire Productions. He helped clients of the radio station who didnt have a web site, build one to tie in with their radio commercials. Greg&#8217;s company was bought out after a successful run and he was made Partner at VeriQik Technology, where he learned about WordPress and Joomla!</p>\n<p>In 2010 he started a new job as Chief Technology Officer at Bluewater Broadcasting in Montgomery, Alabama. In 2011, Greg started using the Genesis Framework for his PSD conversions and was promoted to Chief Engineer.</p>\n<p>Finally, after three and half years at Bluewater, he accepted the position as Front-end Developer here atWebDevStudios! He&#8217;ll be working on converting client websites from Photoshop into custom themes. Greg is thrilled about no longer being on-call or having to worry about something at the radio station breaking while He&#8217;s on vacation!</p>\n<p>He says:</p>\n<blockquote><p>Im very excited to be a part of an agency that is on the forefront of both technology and community. They encourage us to contribute to WordPress, which I think is a great attitude to have toward a product that allows all of us to have cool jobs!</p></blockquote>\n<p>Outside of work, he&#8217;s married to his beautiful wife Tara, and father to a crazy kid named Chase. He loves to cook,enjoy the outdoors, including duck hunting, fishing and camping. Greg is a huge Green Bay Packers fan and loves to play Call of Duty on the Xbox!</p>\n<p>Welcome to the team Greg!</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:79:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/29/wds-welcomes-greg-rickaby-to-our-team/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:66:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"How to set up SSL with OSX Mountain Lions built-in Apache";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:94:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/24/how-to-set-up-ssl-with-osx-mountain-lions-built-in-apache/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:103:"http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/24/how-to-set-up-ssl-with-osx-mountain-lions-built-in-apache/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 24 May 2013 19:38:50 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:9:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"How To";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Tutorial";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Apache";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"https";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"local development";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"localhost";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:6;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Mountain Lion";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:7;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"OSX";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:8;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"SSL";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"http://webdevstudios.com/?p=7462";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:437:"There are many tutorials out there, but for whatever reason I couldn&#8217;t get it work after a first pass. After a little help from some twitter friends (thanks @ryandonsullivan &#38; @andygambles!), I was able to pull together all the necessary &#8230; <a class="more-link" href="http://webdevstudios.com/2013/05/24/how-to-set-up-ssl-with-osx-mountain-lions-built-in-apache/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Jtsternberg";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7003:"<p>There are many tutorials out there, but for whatever reason I couldn&#8217;t get it work after a first pass. After a little help from some twitter friends (thanks <a title="@ryandonsullivan" href="http://twitter.com/ryandonsullivan" target="_blank">@ryandonsullivan</a> &amp; <a title="@andygambles" href="http://twitter.com/andygambles" target="_blank">@andygambles</a>!), I was able to pull together all the necessary pieces (read: remove gremlins from my setup including but not limited to typos) and get it working.</p>\n<p>This will be very thorough, and (I hope) won&#8217;t take anyknowledge for granted.</p>\n<h3>References:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a title="Using SSL for your local development" href="https://www.servage.net/blog/2011/05/19/using-ssl-for-your-local-development/" target="_blank">Using SSL for your local development</a></li>\n<li><a title="Apache SSL on Mac OSX Lion 10.7" href="http://blog.andyhunt.info/2011/11/26/apache-ssl-on-max-osx-lion-10-7" target="_blank">Apache SSL on Mac OSX Lion 10.7</a></li>\n<li><a title="How to create a self-signed SSL Certificate" href="http://www.akadia.com/services/ssh_test_certificate.html" target="_blank">How to create a self-signed SSL Certificate</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Finder App -&gt; Go -&gt; Go to Folder (cmd-shift-g) -&gt; type:\n<pre><code>/private/etc/apache2</code></pre>\n<p>-&gt; hit enter.</li>\n<li>New folder (cmd-shift-n) (OSX may ask for your admin password) -&gt; name the folder &#8216;<strong>ssl</strong>&#8216; -&gt; hit enter</li>\n<li>Create a backup of the &#8216;<strong>httpd.conf</strong>&#8216; file in that folder.</li>\n<li>Open the &#8216;<strong>httpd.conf</strong>&#8216; file (in the apache2 folder that you&#8217;re in) in a text editor. (next several steps taken <a title="Apache SSL on Mac OSX Lion 10.7" href="http://blog.andyhunt.info/2011/11/26/apache-ssl-on-max-osx-lion-10-7/" target="_blank">from here</a>)\n<ol>\n<li>Make sure the SSL module is enabled if it&#8217;s not. Do this by uncommenting (aka, remove the &#8216;#&#8217; symbol in front) the line that looks like:\n<pre><code>LoadModule ssl_module libexec/apache2/mod_ssl.so</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>In the same file search forand uncomment (remove the #) this line:\n<pre><code>Include /private/etc/apache2/extra/httpd-ssl.conf</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>Save the file.(OSX may ask for your admin password)</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Create a backup ofthe &#8216;<strong>httpd-ssl.conf</strong>&#8216; file (in the &#8216;<strong>apache2/extra</strong>&#8216; folder).</li>\n<li>Nowopen the &#8216;<strong>httpd-ssl.conf</strong>&#8216; filein your text editor.\n<ol>\n<li>Update the &#8216;<strong>DocumentRoot</strong>&#8216; line with where your site&#8217;s root folder. In my case I put the path to my WordPress installation I needed to test. Something like:\n<pre><code>DocumentRoot /Users/YOURUSERNAME/Sites/WordPress</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>Make sure &#8216;<strong>ServerName</strong>&#8216; line looks like:\n<pre><code>ServerName localhost</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>modify &#8216;<strong>ServerAdmin</strong>&#8216; line to use one of your email addresses. (I doubt this is necessary)</li>\n<li>Take note of the line &#8216;<strong>ErrorLog</strong>&#8216;. You can use the location listed thereto &#8220;Go to folder&#8221; in finder and view the log if things don&#8217;t work. Or worse-case scenario, you can provide it&#8217;s output to someone smart who might be able to help. <img src=''http://webdevstudios.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif'' alt='':)'' class=''wp-smiley'' /> </li>\n<li>Edit &#8216;<strong>SSLCertificateFile</strong>&#8216; line to point to your new ssl folder and the ssl certificate file (don&#8217;t worry, we&#8217;ll be creating that shortly). That line should look like:\n<pre><code>SSLCertificateFile "/private/etc/apache2/ssl/ssl.crt"</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>Do the same with the &#8216;<strong>SSLCertificateKeyFile</strong>&#8216; line:\n<pre><code>SSLCertificateKeyFile "/private/etc/apache2/ssl/ssl.key"</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>In the same file comment out (add a # to the beginning of the line) the &#8216;<strong>SSLCACertificatePath</strong>&#8216; and &#8216;<strong>SSLCARevocationPath</strong>&#8216; lines if they&#8217;re not already.</li>\n<li>Save the file.(OSX may ask for your admin password)</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Open Terminal app -&gt; Read below caveats, then <a title="How to create a self-signed SSL Certificate" href="http://www.akadia.com/services/ssh_test_certificate.html" target="_blank">follow instructions here</a>\n<ol>\n<li>Each step has a singular line of dark bold text.. that is text you will paste into terminal and hit enter (copy the text exactly, not including white space or line breaks). The blue text below is an example of what terminal will output. (After pasting the line from step 2, terminal will walk you through the certificate&#8217;s necessary info. Whatever you put should be fine.. just hit enter after answering)</li>\n<li>On step 5, replace &#8216;<b>/usr/local/apache/conf/ssl.crt</b>&#8216; with the path to the location of the new &#8216;ssl&#8217; folder you created in finder:<strong>/private/etc/apache2</strong>. So this will look like:\n<pre><code>/private/etc/apache2/ssl/ssl.crt</code></pre>\n<p>Do the same with the ssl.key line. Replace:</p>\n<pre><code>/usr/local/apache/conf/ssl.key</code></pre>\n<p>with:</p>\n<pre><code>/private/etc/apache2/ssl/ssl.key</code></pre>\n<p>If you haven&#8217;t noticed, these values need to line up exactly with the paths you put in the&#8217;<strong>httpd-ssl.conf</strong>&#8216; file.</li>\n<li>Skip step 6 (it&#8217;s already done), and step 7.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>At this point, you should be able to go to <a title="localhost" href="https://localhost" target="_blank">https://localhost</a>and see it working. If you&#8217;re using a good browser, you&#8217;ll probably be warned about the authenticity of the certificate, but unless you have trust issues with yourself, you can ignore the errors. You&#8217;ll probably also notice other indications that you&#8217;re not using a known certificate, but again, you don&#8217;t need to worry about them.\n<p><div id="attachment_3909" class="wp-caption alignnone" style="width: 106px"><img class="size-full wp-image-3909" alt="https-warning" src="http://webdevstudios.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/https-warning.png" width="96" height="44" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Chrome&#8217;s notification</p></div></li>\n</ol>\n<p>*Note: from <a title="Using SSL for your local development" href="https://www.servage.net/blog/2011/05/19/using-ssl-for-your-local-development/" target="_blank">Using SSL for your local development</a>, Beware that Apache only supports one SSL domain per IP. So you need to add further IPs to your system, or use a module that allows multiple SSL VirtualHosts per IP. There is some further reading on this topic<a href="http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/web/library/wa-multissl/index.html" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:99:"http://webdevstudios.com/2